He went overseas?

00:02:48.040 --> 00:02:49.570
Did not go overseas.

00:02:49.570 --> 00:02:51.100
But he was in the military?

00:02:51.100 --> 00:02:53.800
Whoever is in the military,
no matter what they do,

00:02:53.800 --> 00:02:55.860
no matter they serve,
they're all veterans

00:02:55.860 --> 00:02:57.990
and they should be remembered.

00:02:57.990 --> 00:03:00.650
Did someone else have
their hand up over here?

00:03:00.650 --> 00:03:02.510
Yes sir?

00:03:02.510 --> 00:03:05.490
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:03:05.490 --> 00:03:08.200
Your friend's father
was in the Marines.

00:03:08.200 --> 00:03:14.090
So the fact that a lot of you folks
know veterans, have some veterans

00:03:14.090 --> 00:03:19.230
in your family, your friends
have people in veterans,

00:03:19.230 --> 00:03:21.600
that says there's probably
a lot of veterans around.

00:03:21.600 --> 00:03:24.030
And really there are.

00:03:24.030 --> 00:03:28.540
Believe it or not, there
are 20 million veterans

00:03:28.540 --> 00:03:30.260
who are in this country today.

00:03:30.260 --> 00:03:33.810
In this room alone, Mr.
Cole [assumed spelling],

00:03:33.810 --> 00:03:36.030
where'd Mr. Cole go?

00:03:36.030 --> 00:03:38.960
He's a veteran, in the
Army many years ago.

00:03:38.960 --> 00:03:40.580
I was a veteran.

00:03:40.580 --> 00:03:41.880
There's veterans everywhere.

00:03:41.880 --> 00:03:43.800
I bet there's veterans
in your school.

00:03:43.800 --> 00:03:46.480
I bet there's veterans that
live down the street from you.

00:03:46.480 --> 00:03:49.070
I bet there's veterans
you go to church with.

00:03:49.070 --> 00:03:50.660
They're everywhere.

00:03:50.660 --> 00:03:55.990
And each and every one of them have
what we call an important story

00:03:55.990 --> 00:03:57.510
to tell.

00:03:57.510 --> 00:04:01.590
It's a story of serving
their country.

00:04:01.590 --> 00:04:05.030
No matter where they go,
no matter what they do,

00:04:05.030 --> 00:04:06.890
what they do is important.

00:04:06.890 --> 00:04:08.970
Why do you think veterans
are important?

00:04:08.970 --> 00:04:10.270
Anybody have an idea?

00:04:10.270 --> 00:04:11.570
Yes.

00:04:11.570 --> 00:04:15.920
&gt;&gt; Because I think they
fight for [inaudible].

00:04:15.920 --> 00:04:17.260
&gt;&gt; Robert Patrick: Exactly.

00:04:17.260 --> 00:04:22.350 position:56%
They're willing to fight, in some
cases lay down their lives, for each

00:04:22.350 --> 00:04:25.710
and every one of us so that we
can enjoy what we have today

00:04:25.710 --> 00:04:27.010
in this country.

00:04:27.010 --> 00:04:28.530
And that's happened from day one

00:04:28.530 --> 00:04:31.720
from when this country
started all the way up to today

00:04:31.720 --> 00:04:34.690
that there're men and women
who've been willing to do this.

00:04:34.690 --> 00:04:36.840
And that's why we think
those stories are important.

00:04:36.840 --> 00:04:39.360
So we here at the Library
of Congress,

00:04:39.360 --> 00:04:42.080
actually the United
States Congress thought

00:04:42.080 --> 00:04:43.380
that this would be a good idea

00:04:43.380 --> 00:04:46.740
and they created something called
the Veterans History Project.

00:04:46.740 --> 00:04:51.200
And this is a project where
we encourage people to sit

00:04:51.200 --> 00:04:56.030
down with a veteran in their
life, their neighbor, their uncle,

00:04:56.030 --> 00:04:59.430
their mother, their grandmother,
their teacher, whoever,

00:04:59.430 --> 00:05:01.810
and listen to their story.

00:05:01.810 --> 00:05:04.550
And generally this is
done, this is something

00:05:04.550 --> 00:05:08.770
that we ask high school
students and above to do for us.

00:05:08.770 --> 00:05:12.140
And we've had people all
over the country doing this,

00:05:12.140 --> 00:05:13.890
students all over the country.

00:05:13.890 --> 00:05:17.030
We've had people like
in the Red Cross.

00:05:17.030 --> 00:05:19.060
We've had people in
veterans' organizations.

00:05:19.060 --> 00:05:23.430
We've had people in the Department
of Veterans Affairs, just all kinds

00:05:23.430 --> 00:05:26.010
of people recording these stories.

00:05:26.010 --> 00:05:27.980
But you can kind of
be a part of it too.

00:05:27.980 --> 00:05:31.140
And if you want to, you
can go online and hear some

00:05:31.140 --> 00:05:33.170
of these stories on our website.

00:05:33.170 --> 00:05:36.600
But I would also encourage
you to talk about,

00:05:36.600 --> 00:05:40.030
we talked about those veterans you
know or maybe that you don't know

00:05:40.030 --> 00:05:42.370
to sit down and talk to them.

00:05:42.370 --> 00:05:45.250
Ask them what's it
like being in the Arm.

00:05:45.250 --> 00:05:46.590
What'd you do in the Army.

00:05:46.590 --> 00:05:47.890
Where'd you go.

00:05:47.890 --> 00:05:50.120
What was important for you.

00:05:50.120 --> 00:05:52.790
What was some of the funny
things that happened to you?

00:05:52.790 --> 00:05:55.100
Believe it or not, there are
funny things that happen to you

00:05:55.100 --> 00:05:56.400
when you're in the military.

00:05:56.400 --> 00:05:59.380
I have 28 years' worth of them.

00:05:59.380 --> 00:06:03.510
But also ask them what does it mean
for them to say, "I'm a veteran?"

00:06:03.510 --> 00:06:07.320
And when they think back on
their service to their country,

00:06:07.320 --> 00:06:10.950
how they look at that and the
importance they put on that.

00:06:10.950 --> 00:06:13.760
And whether they would
do it all over again.

00:06:13.760 --> 00:06:16.690
And nine times out of ten
they would say they would.

00:06:16.690 --> 00:06:19.050
There's another veteran
sitting back there.

00:06:19.050 --> 00:06:20.350
That young man's a veteran.

00:06:20.350 --> 00:06:21.650
I'm a veteran.

00:06:21.650 --> 00:06:23.630
Mr. Cole's a veteran
who was just here.

00:06:23.630 --> 00:06:25.420
So we're everywhere.

00:06:25.420 --> 00:06:29.750
So that's the story
I have for you today.

00:06:29.750 --> 00:06:33.500
You're going to be
hearing some other stories

00:06:33.500 --> 00:06:37.940
from a very important veteran
that I think Miss Jaffe is going

00:06:37.940 --> 00:06:41.160
to introduce at this time.

00:06:41.160 --> 00:06:45.420
&gt;&gt; Karen Jaffe: Brian
Thacker is a Vietnam vet

00:06:45.420 --> 00:06:48.000
and a Congressional
Medal of Honor winner

00:06:48.000 --> 00:06:51.290
and you're going to
learn all about that.

00:06:51.290 --> 00:06:54.590
And yesterday, which was
Memorial Day, we were talking

00:06:54.590 --> 00:06:56.410
about that a little bit earlier.

