00:08:37.910 --> 00:08:44.500
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: Can we start the
lesson with a fine point for us

00:08:44.500 --> 00:08:49.400
that we think of ourselves
as recipients, not winners.

00:08:49.400 --> 00:08:52.040
We entered no contest.

00:08:53.770 --> 00:09:00.680 position:56%
It's a little thing but it's one
that I've been given the opportunity

00:09:00.680 --> 00:09:04.460
to speak to, coming
out of the shoot.

00:09:05.620 --> 00:09:08.680
Got to get my [inaudible].

00:09:09.950 --> 00:09:14.380
This is not a me award.

00:09:14.380 --> 00:09:17.770
This is an us award.

00:09:17.770 --> 00:09:21.200
Yesterday when I was down at
the Vietnam Veterans Memorial

00:09:21.200 --> 00:09:26.110
and the questions were always
what does this day mean to you,

00:09:26.110 --> 00:09:28.790
what are you thinking about,

00:09:28.790 --> 00:09:33.390
and the short answer is the same
thing I think about every day.

00:09:33.390 --> 00:09:37.780
On panel four west, there's
a place on that panel

00:09:37.780 --> 00:09:42.950
that remembers March 31, 1971.

00:09:42.950 --> 00:09:46.190
And it was an average
day in Vietnam.

00:09:47.490 --> 00:09:52.390
There's nine names on that wall,
in that section and a little

00:09:52.390 --> 00:09:57.280
down about 85 to 95 row levels.

00:09:57.280 --> 00:10:02.970
But for the efforts of five other
people, mine would be the tenth.

00:10:07.120 --> 00:10:12.090
And every day I thank them for the
opportunity for a second chance.

00:10:12.090 --> 00:10:16.120
I hope that when I
walk out of here today,

00:10:16.120 --> 00:10:18.800
you will think that
I did them proud.

00:10:26.050 --> 00:10:37.170
This award is since the Civil War,
just about 3500 soldiers, sailors,

00:10:37.170 --> 00:10:39.440
airmen, coast guard,
one coast guard,

00:10:39.440 --> 00:10:46.040
one woman have received the
honor out of over 40 million

00:10:46.040 --> 00:10:49.870
that have ever served,
same time frame.

00:10:49.870 --> 00:10:57.930
I had nothing to do with
nominating myself for this thing.

00:10:57.930 --> 00:11:00.010
None of us did.

00:11:00.010 --> 00:11:05.050
It was our peers that when
all the dust had settled

00:11:05.050 --> 00:11:10.690
and there's usually a commander
that says, okay, awards,

00:11:10.690 --> 00:11:14.250
what do you think,
who made a difference,

00:11:14.250 --> 00:11:22.930
and somebody nominated us with
me to carry the responsibility

00:11:22.930 --> 00:11:25.520
of receiving the award
and presenting it

00:11:25.520 --> 00:11:29.650
in their behalf, to
whoever I talk to.

00:11:29.650 --> 00:11:32.320
That's the way it is
with all of them today,

00:11:32.320 --> 00:11:34.670
all of the living recipients.

00:11:34.670 --> 00:11:36.330
It wasn't always that way.

00:11:36.330 --> 00:11:42.620
Back in the Civil War, you could
promote yourself and many did.

00:11:42.620 --> 00:11:46.890
And that era has passed.

00:11:51.190 --> 00:11:59.400
This book, "Choosing Courage,"
is not just about this award.

00:11:59.400 --> 00:12:02.620
It's about some civilians
that have done the same thing.

00:12:02.620 --> 00:12:04.850
That would be you.

00:12:04.850 --> 00:12:10.450
There's at least two stories in
there that are from children,

00:12:10.450 --> 00:12:15.720
maybe three if I remember right.

00:12:16.750 --> 00:12:25.260
Doolittle's daughter wrote one
but I knew her as an adult,

00:12:25.260 --> 00:12:28.410
not when she was in sixth grade.

00:12:28.410 --> 00:12:36.820
Jencie's story is a tough one.

00:12:36.820 --> 00:12:47.020
It's a reality in every school
that all of the teachers train for.

00:12:47.020 --> 00:12:49.560
My generation did not.

00:12:49.560 --> 00:12:57.800
It's one of the differences between
the good old bad days in the 1950s

00:12:57.800 --> 00:13:04.110
and yet when I say that
I'm a product of a separate

00:13:04.110 --> 00:13:10.750
and unequal school system,
it hadn't changed over yet.

00:13:10.750 --> 00:13:14.900
Having a weapon in school was
the last thing we thought of.

00:13:14.900 --> 00:13:16.870
I certainly knew how to use them.

00:13:16.870 --> 00:13:20.340
I'd been taught.

00:13:20.340 --> 00:13:23.750
Don't point that thing at me, boy,

00:13:23.750 --> 00:13:26.530
that's the way my uncles
addressed me when I needed

00:13:26.530 --> 00:13:29.100
to improve my behavior and conduct.

00:13:29.100 --> 00:13:37.070
But it was very clear from first
grade on that you shoot at targets.

00:13:37.070 --> 00:13:39.230
If you're hunting, you
shoot at the animal

00:13:39.230 --> 00:13:41.850
but you never point
he weapon at a person.

00:13:41.850 --> 00:13:48.580
And I got that training early on.

00:13:50.230 --> 00:13:54.890
We didn't have weapons
in the schools.

00:13:54.890 --> 00:13:59.970
We had these but that was it.

00:14:05.190 --> 00:14:09.160
The challenge that
Jencie faced was one

00:14:09.160 --> 00:14:12.520
that here we are, we
have to deal with it.

00:14:12.520 --> 00:14:15.990
If you go down to Union
Station and you watch the metro,

00:14:15.990 --> 00:14:22.970
the Amtrak videos, there's a video
there that tells you what to do.

00:14:26.210 --> 00:14:29.540
You only have three choices.

00:14:29.540 --> 00:14:31.500
Two of them are run away.

00:14:31.500 --> 00:14:34.150
And they come first.

00:14:34.150 --> 00:14:39.450
The third one is the
soldier's solution

00:14:39.450 --> 00:14:49.740
and the third solution is attack,
only if you have to because

00:14:49.740 --> 00:14:52.970
at that point you've
already made the decision

00:14:52.970 --> 00:14:55.130
that the shooter that you're next.

00:14:55.130 --> 00:15:02.490
You're trapped and that's an
ugly reality that we all face

00:15:02.490 --> 00:15:05.960
in public spaces and in school.

