I'll probably read about the
young man that she confronted.

00:15:48.150 --> 00:15:52.100
I have not made a phone call
to the Foundation in years

00:15:52.100 --> 00:15:54.530
about what's happened next.

00:15:54.530 --> 00:15:59.740
But when you hear the
date is March 14, 2006,

00:15:59.740 --> 00:16:03.360
Jencie Fagan was a
phys ed teacher setting

00:16:03.360 --> 00:16:05.830
up for volleyball for first period.

00:16:05.830 --> 00:16:09.210
I think you all have been there.

00:16:09.210 --> 00:16:11.770
Some of you might've
been there to help.

00:16:13.010 --> 00:16:18.490
She was at the Edward Pine
Middle School in Reno, Nevada.

00:16:18.490 --> 00:16:22.480
And she was one of the more
popular members of the faculty.

00:16:24.470 --> 00:16:29.900
She had enthusiasm but she
also had high expectations.

00:16:31.930 --> 00:16:36.090
And she was involved with her kids.

00:16:36.090 --> 00:16:41.300
She ran the laps with the kids.

00:16:41.300 --> 00:16:43.850
She encouraged those that were
having trouble to keep up.

00:16:43.850 --> 00:16:47.740
She ran with you to
try to help you along

00:16:47.740 --> 00:16:51.440
because running is a challenge.

00:16:51.440 --> 00:16:54.300
I don't like to do it.

00:16:54.300 --> 00:16:57.060
But it's one of those
things that you have to do

00:16:57.060 --> 00:17:01.430
to develop your lungs,
to develop your body.

00:17:01.430 --> 00:17:07.070
The bad news is that the
lungs mature next to last.

00:17:08.250 --> 00:17:12.380
The last to mature is
this thing up here.

00:17:12.380 --> 00:17:19.970
But if you don't exercise
both before you get there,

00:17:19.970 --> 00:17:27.430
you don't come out as strong.

00:17:29.490 --> 00:17:33.010
Anyway, James, I don't know if
that's his real name or it's

00:17:33.010 --> 00:17:36.840
to protect him, was one of
the loners at Edward Pine.

00:17:36.840 --> 00:17:39.020
School was a struggle.

00:17:39.020 --> 00:17:42.560
He had a dark feeling that
no one, not his schoolmates,

00:17:42.560 --> 00:17:45.670
his parents, cared about him.

00:17:45.670 --> 00:17:48.160
He was angry, confused.

00:17:48.160 --> 00:17:54.970
It had come to a boil when he
watched a video of Columbine.

00:18:01.690 --> 00:18:03.070
He came to school that morning

00:18:03.070 --> 00:18:05.870
with a 0.38 caliber
pistol in his backpack.

00:18:05.870 --> 00:18:12.790
Went to the boys room,
loaded it, and came out ready

00:18:12.790 --> 00:18:22.080
to shoot before first period.

00:18:22.080 --> 00:18:26.070
One of his friends, he
did have at least one,

00:18:26.070 --> 00:18:30.600
he didn't recognize it though,
passed him and asked him

00:18:30.600 --> 00:18:32.820
to take the gun away,
put the gun away,

00:18:32.820 --> 00:18:36.310
and then James told him
to run for his life.

00:18:36.310 --> 00:18:38.610
And then he opened fire.

00:18:41.570 --> 00:18:44.740
Jencie recognized the sounds.

00:18:47.510 --> 00:18:49.970
There were three rounds.

00:18:51.010 --> 00:18:57.040
And she sprinted to the sound
even though she didn't have to.

00:18:57.040 --> 00:18:59.940
The first rule when you hear
those sounds is to move away.

00:19:06.430 --> 00:19:08.280
Code Red had been sounded.

00:19:08.280 --> 00:19:11.820
That was their emergency signal.

00:19:14.250 --> 00:19:17.370
Jencie huddled as many
students as she could

00:19:17.370 --> 00:19:21.460
into the offices along
the way to the gym.

00:19:24.490 --> 00:19:26.110
One of her students said, yeah,

00:19:26.110 --> 00:19:28.770
we kind of expected Jencie
to come to the rescue.

00:19:28.770 --> 00:19:31.070
That's the kind of
teacher that she was.

00:19:35.640 --> 00:19:38.450
And then she saw James.

00:19:38.450 --> 00:19:45.960
And she walked up to him
and started talking to him,

00:19:45.960 --> 00:19:52.080
not in a loud yelling voice at all.

00:19:52.080 --> 00:19:54.680
You talk in a soft voice.

00:19:59.310 --> 00:20:03.320
The book says she began
talking to him in a soft voice.

00:20:03.320 --> 00:20:05.330
She kept telling him
that he was not a killer

00:20:05.330 --> 00:20:07.940
and that he would be all right.

00:20:07.940 --> 00:20:10.670
You know, worried that someone else
could come in to the cafeteria,

00:20:10.670 --> 00:20:15.400
he'd turn and shoot, so she stood
in front of him to make sure

00:20:15.400 --> 00:20:16.900
that if he was going
to pull the trigger,

00:20:16.900 --> 00:20:19.200
she was going to take
the first round.

00:20:24.390 --> 00:20:27.510
She wasn't angry with James at all.

00:20:28.810 --> 00:20:32.750
She felt sympathy and was
determined to keep him

00:20:32.750 --> 00:20:36.270
from hurting anybody else.

00:20:36.270 --> 00:20:41.140
She remembered her own
difficulties growing up.

00:20:41.140 --> 00:20:45.070
One of six kids, brought up by
a single mother, in a small town

00:20:45.070 --> 00:20:53.370
in Alabama, she felt disadvantaged
in comparison to normal families.

00:20:53.370 --> 00:20:58.230
But her mom who worked
wouldn't tolerate self pity

00:20:58.230 --> 00:21:01.930
and she was taught
mom didn't give up.

00:21:01.930 --> 00:21:03.230
She pushed us harder.

00:21:03.230 --> 00:21:05.530
She taught us to never quit.

00:21:08.170 --> 00:21:11.610
And that's one of the
things that made her stick

00:21:11.610 --> 00:21:13.970
with James rather than run.

00:21:20.930 --> 00:21:26.360
She asked him to put down the
gun, please put it on the floor.

00:21:26.360 --> 00:21:31.990
As long as you've got that thing,
we're in an unstable situation.

00:21:31.990 --> 00:21:41.200
As soon as he did put it down, she
hugged him and kept talking to him.

00:21:41.200 --> 00:21:43.490
She said we're not going anywhere.

00:21:43.490 --> 00:21:44.840
I'm going to be with you.

00:21:44.840 --> 00:21:47.720
I'll see you through this.

00:21:47.720 --> 00:21:52.500
You have at least one
teacher on your side.

00:21:52.500 --> 00:21:54.800
Yep.

00:21:59.730 --> 00:22:02.570
The part that I'm unhappy about
because I don't know the rest

00:22:02.570 --> 00:22:05.320
of the story on this side
is, you know, James was --

00:22:05.320 --> 00:22:06.660
Two students were treated.

00:22:06.660 --> 00:22:10.500
He did wound two students.

00:22:10.500 --> 00:22:16.290
He was tried as a minor, arrested,
tried, convicted of two counts

00:22:16.290 --> 00:22:21.440
of battery with a deadly weapon,
and I'm sure he went for treatment.

00:22:21.440 --> 00:22:26.300
What I don't know is what's
happened to him since.

00:22:26.300 --> 00:22:31.580
And that bothers me.

00:22:31.580 --> 00:22:40.710
When she was asked why she
had put herself in harm's way,

00:22:40.710 --> 00:22:43.010
Jencie talked about her mother.

00:22:46.460 --> 00:22:49.200
She taught us to think that
if you see something happening

00:22:49.200 --> 00:22:52.270
that isn't right, you do something.

00:22:52.270 --> 00:22:56.790
You don't look for
someone else to handle it.

00:22:56.790 --> 00:23:01.460
She said I'm a teacher,
a mom, a human being.

00:23:01.460 --> 00:23:04.350
These are our children.

00:23:04.350 --> 00:23:09.220
There's no way I'm going to call a
parent after something has happened

00:23:09.220 --> 00:23:11.540
and tell them that I
didn't do everything I could

00:23:11.540 --> 00:23:13.880
to protect their child.

00:23:19.410 --> 00:23:24.930 position:56%
A couple years later in 2008, March
25, that's a significant day for us,

00:23:24.930 --> 00:23:28.670
it's the Medal of Honors' birthday.

00:23:28.670 --> 00:23:32.270
We celebrate it.

00:23:32.270 --> 00:23:34.640
We recognized Jencie.

00:23:34.640 --> 00:23:37.150
I think she was one of
our first recipients

00:23:37.150 --> 00:23:41.330
of our citizens above
self recognition.

00:23:41.330 --> 00:23:46.510
That was a dream come true.

00:23:46.510 --> 00:23:53.790 position:56%
We think as recipients that we need
to recognize people in civilian life

00:23:53.790 --> 00:23:59.290
when they step up to the
plate and it's a small token

00:23:59.290 --> 00:24:03.430 position:56%
of our appreciation to Jencie Fagan.

00:24:03.430 --> 00:24:08.420
What she did when facing
harm was every bit

00:24:08.420 --> 00:24:11.350
as courageous as what
a soldier faces.

00:24:11.350 --> 00:24:19.240
And that is an abbreviated
version of what's in print here.

00:24:19.240 --> 00:24:22.050
I skipped some of the
words and inserted some

00:24:22.050 --> 00:24:25.290
of my own comments along the way.

00:24:25.290 --> 00:24:31.500
But it's a short story,
unfortunately one

00:24:31.500 --> 00:24:35.680
that almost every school
has to be aware of.

00:24:43.190 --> 00:24:47.490
Now I think comes the hard part.

00:24:47.490 --> 00:24:51.940
I'm supposed to talk about me.

00:24:55.570 --> 00:25:00.970 position:56%
I never know what to say on that and
we'll open it up for questions next.

00:25:09.090 --> 00:25:10.650
We were soldiers.

00:25:10.650 --> 00:25:12.290
We were in Vietnam.

00:25:12.290 --> 00:25:16.890
We were on a isolated
small fire base.

00:25:16.890 --> 00:25:21.560
The only way we could get
to it was by helicopter

00:25:21.560 --> 00:25:28.230
because it was surrounded with
North Vietnamese regulars.

00:25:28.230 --> 00:25:36.390
On March 31, the North Vietnamese
decided they wanted the fire base.

00:25:36.390 --> 00:25:40.620
And we didn't want to give it up.

00:25:46.870 --> 00:25:51.590
I lost three men, very quickly,
because they were awake.

00:25:51.590 --> 00:25:56.610
They were on duty,
5:30 in the morning,

00:25:56.610 --> 00:25:59.780
6 o'clock in the morning
you're supposed to be asleep,

00:25:59.780 --> 00:26:03.490
unless you're a soldier
in a combat zone.

00:26:03.490 --> 00:26:06.920
And then you either have a third
or half of your people awake,

00:26:06.920 --> 00:26:10.480
ready to fight all the time.

00:26:10.480 --> 00:26:12.840
That was a rotating duty.

00:26:12.840 --> 00:26:17.900
My turn would've been the
day before or the day after.

00:26:17.900 --> 00:26:20.150
We just took turns being up,

00:26:20.150 --> 00:26:22.970
taking watch at all hours
of the day and night.

00:26:35.490 --> 00:26:38.210
We were outnumbered, outgunned.

00:26:38.210 --> 00:26:44.460
The only advantage that we
had is that we were on top

00:26:44.460 --> 00:26:48.640
of the hill shooting down and
they had to shoot up at us.

00:26:48.640 --> 00:26:56.450
But eventually by the end of the
day, we were not going to be able

00:26:56.450 --> 00:27:02.970
to hold that position for that next
night and wait for reinforcements.

00:27:07.150 --> 00:27:10.770 position:56%
In order to get people away, I asked
for artillery fire on that position

00:27:10.770 --> 00:27:18.140
so that they could form up in what
turned out to be a small platoon,

00:27:18.140 --> 00:27:19.690
move down a trail through a place

00:27:19.690 --> 00:27:21.980
where they could be
extracted safely.

00:27:21.980 --> 00:27:27.310
I was waiting for that
fire to get to me

00:27:27.310 --> 00:27:34.710
and it was taking much too long
for me, seconds if you were

00:27:34.710 --> 00:27:36.730
down at the firing battery.

00:27:36.730 --> 00:27:44.690
And I wanted to make darn sure
that when I left the first base,

00:27:44.690 --> 00:27:48.980
and there was one South Vietnamese
soldier standing right beside me.

00:27:48.980 --> 00:27:53.850
He had the machine gun.

00:27:53.850 --> 00:27:56.670
They weren't messing with him.

00:27:56.670 --> 00:27:58.640
They could listen to
us on the radio.

00:27:58.640 --> 00:28:02.210
They knew that I was going
to shoot the location.

00:28:02.210 --> 00:28:06.210
It was just a matter of do we
want to rush across that fire base

00:28:06.210 --> 00:28:09.930
and try to get to them or do we
want to hold back and let them go.

00:28:11.100 --> 00:28:15.640
I don't know what was going
through the enemy commander's mind.

00:28:15.640 --> 00:28:20.680
What I was looking to do at
that point in time was buy time

00:28:20.680 --> 00:28:26.830
so that what was left of a
friendly unit could separate.

00:28:26.830 --> 00:28:29.620
Hopefully there wasn't an
ambush waiting for them.

00:28:29.620 --> 00:28:33.280
And they could get to a place
farther away from the fire base

00:28:33.280 --> 00:28:38.310
where helicopters could
land and extract them.

00:28:38.310 --> 00:28:39.920
I tried to catch up.

00:28:39.920 --> 00:28:48.180
Did not. Ended up deciding that it
was better to stay still and hide

00:28:48.180 --> 00:28:52.100 position:56%
where I wasn't supposed to be and
hope that they wouldn't look for me.

00:28:52.100 --> 00:28:59.570
And that was a successful
strategy the first night.

00:28:59.570 --> 00:29:09.900 position:56%
The next day I was trying to move to
a safer location and we got bombed.

00:29:09.900 --> 00:29:12.680
And when the dust settled,
I was surrounded

00:29:12.680 --> 00:29:15.740
by a North Vietnamese
machine gun position.

00:29:15.740 --> 00:29:22.370
And I had to wait in a bamboo
thicket that had been prepared

00:29:22.370 --> 00:29:27.940
by some animal, probably a
tiger, when I think back on it.

00:29:27.940 --> 00:29:35.560
And I just had to wait until I
thought it was safe to go back

00:29:35.560 --> 00:29:41.490
up to the fire base, which had been
retaken by the South Vietnamese.

00:29:41.490 --> 00:29:42.880
There was a battle going on.

00:29:42.880 --> 00:29:45.870
You could hear it all day.

00:29:45.870 --> 00:29:50.600
Whenever helicopters came in
to resupply the fire base,

00:29:50.600 --> 00:29:53.460
they flew right over my position.

00:29:53.460 --> 00:29:57.280
The machine gun -- The North
Vietnamese machine gun emplacement

00:29:57.280 --> 00:30:04.090
opened up on them and they
either had to go up, go around,

00:30:04.090 --> 00:30:08.150
maneuver to land at the fire base.

00:30:08.150 --> 00:30:09.800
We got strafed every day.

00:30:09.800 --> 00:30:16.290
We knew that a resupply was coming
because we got strafed followed

00:30:16.290 --> 00:30:22.000
by the supply helicopters and
the North Vietnamese just stayed

00:30:22.000 --> 00:30:25.000
in their little holes and waited
for the strafe to end and came up

00:30:25.000 --> 00:30:28.540
and were read to shoot at the
next round of helicopters.

00:30:28.540 --> 00:30:31.080
It was a pretty simple game.

00:30:31.080 --> 00:30:35.570
And eventually I decided
I had to crawl back

00:30:35.570 --> 00:30:40.800
up the mountain and
was successful here.

00:30:40.800 --> 00:30:43.410
I was thirsty.

00:30:43.410 --> 00:30:44.710
I was tired.

00:30:44.710 --> 00:30:46.270
I was hungry.

00:30:46.270 --> 00:30:47.570
Mostly thirsty.

00:30:47.570 --> 00:30:52.000
And I was evacuated and two

00:30:52.000 --> 00:30:54.690
and a half years later
I got the phone call

00:30:54.690 --> 00:30:56.400
that you're going to be decorated.

00:30:56.400 --> 00:31:01.940
And that, sort of in a
nutshell, is my story,

00:31:01.940 --> 00:31:07.560
whatever I could pull
up today and remember.

00:31:07.560 --> 00:31:12.420
I don't know to this day
what I did that was heroic.

00:31:12.420 --> 00:31:16.930
I had a job to do.

00:31:16.930 --> 00:31:19.310
I was the team leader.

00:31:19.310 --> 00:31:20.810
They were my men.

00:31:20.810 --> 00:31:26.340
I had tools at my disposal.

00:31:26.340 --> 00:31:31.010
I used every one of them
to the extent I could.

00:31:31.010 --> 00:31:38.610
But I think that's what
I was expected to do.

00:31:38.610 --> 00:31:40.250
I have to trust my colleagues

00:31:40.250 --> 00:31:44.840
that whatever they saw
trust their judgment

00:31:44.840 --> 00:31:50.990
because that's what we were doing
because you don't give an order,

00:31:50.990 --> 00:31:54.670
an order that you give that
nobody follows is useless.

00:31:54.670 --> 00:31:57.950
People have to accept the
guidance and the instruction.

00:32:01.530 --> 00:32:06.170
But they did put me in and it
survived all the reviews and two

00:32:06.170 --> 00:32:08.900
and a half years later
I was decorated.

00:32:12.810 --> 00:32:17.920
Hopefully, I don't know,
we'll know from your questions

00:32:17.920 --> 00:32:23.900
because that's what's going to come
next after about one or two lines.

00:32:23.900 --> 00:32:26.320
So I'll give you a
break, give you a chance.

00:32:26.320 --> 00:32:28.460 position:56%
I joined the Medal of Honor Society.

00:32:28.460 --> 00:32:35.330
In 1973 there was almost
400 living recipients.

00:32:35.330 --> 00:32:43.790
I got to meet guys from World
War I, II, the Interim, Korea.

00:32:43.790 --> 00:32:48.870
All the people in this
book I've known.

00:32:48.870 --> 00:32:51.200
It's kind of neat.

00:32:51.200 --> 00:32:52.500
It's personal.

00:32:52.500 --> 00:32:56.350
But it's all after Vietnam.

00:32:56.350 --> 00:33:03.140
That the book was published
is a dream come true,

00:33:03.140 --> 00:33:11.020
that we can recognize people like
Jencie Fagan is a dream come true.

00:33:11.020 --> 00:33:14.200
It's something we've wanted to do.

00:33:14.200 --> 00:33:16.980
We've worked hard to do.

00:33:16.980 --> 00:33:20.920
With the help of a lot of other
people, we can make it happen.

00:33:25.090 --> 00:33:27.880
And we hope that you pay attention.

00:33:31.190 --> 00:33:34.530
A lot of people trying to
get you to pay attention.

00:33:34.530 --> 00:33:36.400
I know that.

00:33:36.400 --> 00:33:40.880
And this is one way we hope
we get a sound bite in.

00:33:40.880 --> 00:33:44.270
Do you have any questions?

00:33:44.270 --> 00:33:47.060
Yes ma'am.

00:33:47.060 --> 00:33:51.260
Yeah, you get to practice
using the microphone.

00:33:51.260 --> 00:33:53.480
Say your name.

00:33:53.480 --> 00:33:57.140
&gt;&gt; My name is Cassandra
