00:37:30.430 --> 00:37:32.630
&gt;&gt; My name D'Kaya [phonetic].

00:37:32.630 --> 00:37:38.630
When you served in the Army, did
it make you proud [inaudible]?

00:37:39.710 --> 00:37:42.430
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: I'm
very proud of my service.

00:37:42.430 --> 00:37:48.620
I'm proud of the people I was with.

00:37:48.620 --> 00:37:53.020 position:56%
They were from all over the country.

00:37:53.020 --> 00:37:58.970
And they were good soldiers.

00:37:58.970 --> 00:38:03.140
And they wanted to come home and
they were willing to work together

00:38:03.140 --> 00:38:05.970
to come home rather
than by themselves.

00:38:13.170 --> 00:38:17.130
I wouldn't -- It's one of those
things that you don't want people

00:38:17.130 --> 00:38:19.480
to have to go in the Army.

00:38:19.480 --> 00:38:21.310
You don't want war.

00:38:21.310 --> 00:38:28.640
But if you have to, it seems
like almost every generation

00:38:28.640 --> 00:38:33.060
in our country has had to.

00:38:33.060 --> 00:38:38.870
It's kind of like learning what to
do when there's a weapon in school.

00:38:38.870 --> 00:38:40.540
It's not what you want.

00:38:40.540 --> 00:38:42.490
It's not what you like.

00:38:42.490 --> 00:38:47.590
But it's an ugly reality of
what you have to life with.

00:38:47.590 --> 00:38:49.890
And --

00:38:55.180 --> 00:38:57.440
I'm perfectly willing to
come back to you but I want

00:38:57.440 --> 00:39:01.570
to see somebody else get
their questions in too.

00:39:05.630 --> 00:39:06.930
Follow-up question?

00:39:06.930 --> 00:39:13.010
&gt;&gt; Did you have any family members
when you was in the Army, well,

00:39:13.010 --> 00:39:15.030
like, was you married back then?

00:39:15.030 --> 00:39:18.400
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: Okay,
no, I was not married.

00:39:18.400 --> 00:39:22.070
My father is an Air Force officer.

00:39:22.070 --> 00:39:24.560
And I grew up in the Air Force.

00:39:24.560 --> 00:39:28.220
Let him have it first.

00:39:28.220 --> 00:39:31.030
&gt;&gt; My name Isaiah.

00:39:31.030 --> 00:39:38.100
And what it is like
to be in the Army?

00:39:38.100 --> 00:39:40.850
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: When
you're in the Army,

00:39:40.850 --> 00:39:44.660
you go where the Army wants
you to go, first of all.

00:39:44.660 --> 00:39:50.640
I got very used to living
out of a duffle bag.

00:39:50.640 --> 00:39:55.910
Everything I owned and needed
was in a small suitcase.

00:39:56.940 --> 00:39:59.770
You only need three
pair of underwear.

00:40:03.510 --> 00:40:06.870 position:56%
One that you got on, one that's
clean and one that's in the laundry.

00:40:11.370 --> 00:40:14.480
You quickly learn it's
nice to have a fourth,

00:40:14.480 --> 00:40:16.790
just in case the laundry
doesn't work.

00:40:16.790 --> 00:40:21.630
Same with your uniform.

00:40:21.630 --> 00:40:27.460
Two pairs of boots, one that
you've got on, one that's resting

00:40:27.460 --> 00:40:31.870
and you switch off every day.

00:40:31.870 --> 00:40:36.770
The first thing you do
is you brush your teeth.

00:40:36.770 --> 00:40:39.530 position:56%
Then you wash the rest of your body,

00:40:39.530 --> 00:40:41.970
depending on how much
water you have.

00:40:45.670 --> 00:40:49.490 position:56%
Of course, you're training to do the
one thing that we don't want to do

00:40:49.490 --> 00:40:53.030
as humans and that's
hurt somebody else.

00:40:53.030 --> 00:40:57.700
It goes against every
grain in your body.

00:40:57.700 --> 00:41:00.610
But that's what you're
training to do.

00:41:00.610 --> 00:41:04.400
&gt;&gt; Karen Jaffe: Brian, I
have a question for you.

00:41:04.400 --> 00:41:08.320
In reading this book,
one of the points I got

00:41:08.320 --> 00:41:14.670
of it was the universality
of certain characteristics

00:41:14.670 --> 00:41:20.210
of both outstanding military
soldiers who were recipients

00:41:20.210 --> 00:41:22.990
of the medal and citizens

00:41:22.990 --> 00:41:26.730
who received the honor
medal from the Society.

00:41:26.730 --> 00:41:29.910
So I wondered if you could
talk a bit about some

00:41:29.910 --> 00:41:36.090
of these important characteristics
about courage that are applicable

00:41:36.090 --> 00:41:42.990
to everyone, including our
students from L Pine School.

00:41:42.990 --> 00:41:45.990
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: I'll try.

00:41:45.990 --> 00:41:50.010
The enemy is selfishness.

00:41:50.010 --> 00:42:01.230
The enemy is me, I, and thinking
that the world revolves around me,

00:42:01.230 --> 00:42:04.400
and accepting the reality
that it doesn't,

00:42:04.400 --> 00:42:11.130
that there's something bigger
than you, more important than you,

00:42:11.130 --> 00:42:17.870
and that you can get along a whole
lot better if you think that way.

00:42:22.430 --> 00:42:25.380
The most -- One of the
most fundamental instincts

00:42:25.380 --> 00:42:30.900
that we all have is self
preservation and I want me

00:42:30.900 --> 00:42:37.530
to be saved first as opposed
to me being saved last.

00:42:37.530 --> 00:42:43.170
If you make me saved first,
you're going to have regrets

00:42:43.170 --> 00:42:45.470
for the rest of your life.

00:42:52.710 --> 00:42:56.610
Even though it may be more
difficult in the short run

00:42:56.610 --> 00:43:02.970
to say save me last,
if you are saved.

00:43:02.970 --> 00:43:07.980
You don't wonder, could
I have done more.

00:43:07.980 --> 00:43:13.620
What about if I'd only
done this, then maybe one

00:43:13.620 --> 00:43:17.100
or two more would've made it.

00:43:17.100 --> 00:43:20.920
I still think about the men I lost.

00:43:20.920 --> 00:43:23.500
Is there anything that we
could've done differently.

00:43:23.500 --> 00:43:29.330
And at the end of the day,
no, we were going to have two

00:43:29.330 --> 00:43:35.240 position:56%
or three people on duty that morning
that were going to be fully armed,

00:43:35.240 --> 00:43:40.780
loaded, letting the rest of us
catch a few Z's, a few more Z's.

00:43:40.780 --> 00:43:44.580
And that when the attack
came, they were the ones

00:43:44.580 --> 00:43:46.880
that were going to be on the line.

00:43:51.620 --> 00:43:53.260
And I lost them very early.

00:43:53.260 --> 00:43:56.190
I can't change that.

00:43:56.190 --> 00:44:01.560
The others, yeah, we could've
tried to bug out early

00:44:01.560 --> 00:44:04.970
and we would've all, none of us
would be here to talk about it.

00:44:11.500 --> 00:44:16.210
In all of the stories in
there, it's an individual

00:44:16.210 --> 00:44:21.590
who was putting other
people ahead of themselves

00:44:21.590 --> 00:44:26.590
and it makes a difference
whether it be Jencie

00:44:26.590 --> 00:44:29.220
or Dr. Cox [assumed
spelling] who was the doctor

00:44:29.220 --> 00:44:32.050
from the Doctors Without Borders.

00:44:33.280 --> 00:44:36.880
There are other individuals that
eventually their stories will get

00:44:36.880 --> 00:44:40.530
in to print and will
be added to that.

00:44:41.700 --> 00:44:48.970
I'm thinking of one detective up
in Philadelphia that got a medal

00:44:48.970 --> 00:44:54.210
from the 8-year-old that he
saved in the river that day.

00:44:54.210 --> 00:44:56.920
That award means more
to him than ours.

00:44:56.920 --> 00:45:00.540
And that's the difference
that he made on that day.

00:45:10.650 --> 00:45:12.970
You had another question.

00:45:19.190 --> 00:45:21.490
&gt;&gt; What is the --

00:45:31.510 --> 00:45:33.150
I forgot.

00:45:33.150 --> 00:45:36.570
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: It'll
