00:45:46.310 --> 00:45:47.610
Yes sir.

00:45:47.610 --> 00:45:50.470
&gt;&gt; So my question is
what was it like --

00:45:50.470 --> 00:45:55.940 position:56%
What was your experience like coming
out of the military [inaudible]?

00:45:55.940 --> 00:46:00.230
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: My whole
experience, even in Vietnam, was,

00:46:00.230 --> 00:46:04.620
when I reflect on it, not normal.

00:46:04.620 --> 00:46:11.820
But when I came home, I came
home to a military base,

00:46:11.820 --> 00:46:17.710
where everybody there had
already returned home.

00:46:17.710 --> 00:46:22.060
So from startle response was
everyone knew what it was.

00:46:22.060 --> 00:46:24.160
We all laughed about it.

00:46:24.160 --> 00:46:26.590
And it's okay.

00:46:26.590 --> 00:46:28.090
We've all done that.

00:46:28.090 --> 00:46:30.630
We still are jumpy.

00:46:30.630 --> 00:46:34.060
Anything else going on and
they talk to you about it.

00:46:34.060 --> 00:46:38.610
And instead of being
different, I was with people

00:46:38.610 --> 00:46:42.970
who were the same and
they understood.

00:46:46.040 --> 00:46:54.880
I was in a state that was pro
military, the state of Hawaii,

00:46:54.880 --> 00:46:59.790
not one that you would
expect would be pro military

00:46:59.790 --> 00:47:03.450
but the state is very pro military.

00:47:03.450 --> 00:47:07.830
As a people, they are very
pleased and proud and be Americans

00:47:07.830 --> 00:47:10.280
and they understand
that that Navy base

00:47:10.280 --> 00:47:13.790
at Pearl Harbor has a
lot to do with that.

00:47:13.790 --> 00:47:19.730
And they're very proud of now
it's their grandfather who served

00:47:19.730 --> 00:47:26.750
in the 442 or the 100th

00:47:26.750 --> 00:47:31.010
in the Japanese regiments
that fought in Europe.

00:47:31.010 --> 00:47:35.350
They fought for their citizenship.

00:47:35.350 --> 00:47:38.450
And they're very proud of it.

00:47:38.450 --> 00:47:42.970
So I was in a friendly,
understanding environment.

00:47:44.130 --> 00:47:50.490
And by the time I got to
graduate school in '73,

00:47:50.490 --> 00:47:54.350
my own generation was getting
over that and we were trying

00:47:54.350 --> 00:47:59.920
to get back together again.

00:47:59.920 --> 00:48:03.110
Eventually we'll heal.

00:48:03.110 --> 00:48:06.200
That's work in progress.

00:48:06.200 --> 00:48:07.730
Yes ma'am.

00:48:07.730 --> 00:48:09.310
You remembered?

00:48:09.310 --> 00:48:17.840
&gt;&gt; What is the ITC,
NTC, ITC, I don't know?

00:48:17.840 --> 00:48:19.260
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: ITC?

00:48:19.260 --> 00:48:20.560
&gt;&gt; ROTC.

00:48:20.560 --> 00:48:21.860
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: ROTC?

00:48:21.860 --> 00:48:26.630
Okay. It's Reserve
Officers Training Corps.

00:48:26.630 --> 00:48:33.340
It's a military school
command structure

00:48:33.340 --> 00:48:37.860
that helps college
students become officers.

00:48:37.860 --> 00:48:41.870
In many colleges it's a
minor in military science.

00:48:41.870 --> 00:48:45.830
You'll find it in the
department of social studies.

00:48:45.830 --> 00:48:47.130
You're done?

00:48:47.130 --> 00:48:49.430
&gt;&gt; Yes.

00:48:53.790 --> 00:48:55.090
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: Yes ma'am.

00:48:55.090 --> 00:48:57.690
&gt;&gt; I was going to ask a similar
question [inaudible] does have ROTC

00:48:57.690 --> 00:48:59.060
for high school students

00:48:59.060 --> 00:49:03.690
and our building actually
shares the [inaudible] building

00:49:03.690 --> 00:49:06.180
with the ROTC headquarters.

00:49:06.180 --> 00:49:09.720
They're in our middle school.

00:49:09.720 --> 00:49:15.200
And so I know our kids see it a lot

00:49:15.200 --> 00:49:22.200
and they're not sure what
exactly the ROTC wing is about.

00:49:22.200 --> 00:49:28.460
And so I was just wondering if you
got any advice for them or any sort

00:49:28.460 --> 00:49:32.950
of decision-making advice when it
comes, when they get in high school

00:49:32.950 --> 00:49:36.980
and they have the opportunity
to join ROTC?

00:49:36.980 --> 00:49:39.570
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: When
I was in sixth grade,

00:49:39.570 --> 00:49:42.510
I didn't know what I wanted to do.

00:49:42.510 --> 00:49:48.390
It wasn't until eighth grade that I
even realized that I wanted to fly.

00:49:48.390 --> 00:49:50.340
Still do. I'm too blind
but in the back,

00:49:50.340 --> 00:49:52.200
one of the things that's
driven a lot

00:49:52.200 --> 00:49:55.960
of my decision making was
how do I become a pilot.

00:50:01.600 --> 00:50:07.410
Junior ROTC in high school
is an interesting program.

00:50:07.410 --> 00:50:09.710
It's not for everybody.

00:50:09.710 --> 00:50:16.080
It's one that you need to
look at but it's a program

00:50:19.470 --> 00:50:25.750
that gives you a sense of belonging
to something bigger than yourself.

00:50:25.750 --> 00:50:32.620
They do -- It is -- They do
have some discipline in it.

00:50:32.620 --> 00:50:39.580
Like Jencie Fagan, the cadre
tend to have high expectations

00:50:39.580 --> 00:50:42.640
of the students that do it.

00:50:42.640 --> 00:50:47.910
So if you're -- Some
students in high school need

00:50:47.910 --> 00:50:52.390
that for structure, for help.

00:50:52.390 --> 00:50:58.070
Others don't and would
chafe at the regimentation.

00:50:58.070 --> 00:51:06.180
You have to first look in and learn
to know yourself, what do I need

00:51:06.180 --> 00:51:14.680
and then will this help me
get to where I want to get.

00:51:16.950 --> 00:51:20.070
I have to admit, in sixth grade
I wasn't thinking that way.

00:51:20.070 --> 00:51:24.640
That would've been a stretch.

00:51:24.640 --> 00:51:29.470
But by eighth grade,
it was -- I was very --

00:51:29.470 --> 00:51:34.750 position:56%
I had some skill in the STEM side
of [inaudible], so I kind of pointed

00:51:34.750 --> 00:51:42.280
that way as preparation
for being a pilot.

00:51:42.280 --> 00:51:46.010
Somebody waiving their
hand with another question?

00:51:46.010 --> 00:51:47.310
[ Inaudible Comment ]

00:51:47.310 --> 00:51:49.610
Yes ma'am.

00:51:52.530 --> 00:51:55.820
&gt;&gt; My name is Oshay [phonetic] and
I wonder who was your inspiration

00:51:55.820 --> 00:51:58.120
when you went to the Army?

00:52:00.530 --> 00:52:06.670
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: When I was young,
my parents, my dad in particular,

00:52:06.670 --> 00:52:10.990
was my mentor, was who inspired me.

00:52:10.990 --> 00:52:16.590
As I've gotten older
and older and older,

00:52:22.570 --> 00:52:28.950
I look at a couple of middle school
teachers, junior high teachers

00:52:33.120 --> 00:52:38.510
who had high expectations
for their students,

00:52:38.510 --> 00:52:47.910
were strict about your behavior
in class, Miss [inaudible]

00:52:47.910 --> 00:52:53.650 position:56%
in eighth grade was the first one
to give me leadership responsibility

00:52:53.650 --> 00:52:57.510
on the fire patrol and
later on the safety patrol.

00:53:00.010 --> 00:53:06.360 position:56%
Somebody has to tell you that along
the way and identify it and point it

00:53:06.360 --> 00:53:14.000 position:56%
out to your parents that this one
has potential in the following area.

00:53:14.000 --> 00:53:16.830
I can see it already.

00:53:16.830 --> 00:53:23.790
Miss Hall in Montgomery, Alabama,
ninth grade Latin teacher,

00:53:23.790 --> 00:53:29.310
taught us more English in that
Latin class and taught us more

00:53:29.310 --> 00:53:34.720
about English in that
Latin class than we had had

00:53:34.720 --> 00:53:40.520
in our English teacher but
she was an experienced teacher

00:53:40.520 --> 00:53:42.440
and could do that.

00:53:42.440 --> 00:53:48.030
It was not fair to ask a first-year
teacher who was an art major

00:53:48.030 --> 00:53:50.570
to teach ninth graders English.

00:53:50.570 --> 00:53:56.260
But Miss Hall had no
problem teaching English,

00:53:56.260 --> 00:53:58.010
Latin, any of the courses.

00:53:58.010 --> 00:54:01.590
I think she could've taught
any class in that middle school

00:54:01.590 --> 00:54:03.440
at the ninth grade level.

00:54:03.440 --> 00:54:04.740
She was that good.

00:54:04.740 --> 00:54:09.410
&gt;&gt; Brain, can I ask a question.

00:54:09.410 --> 00:54:10.710
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: Yes sir.

00:54:10.710 --> 00:54:15.060
&gt;&gt; My name is [inaudible]
and my question is

00:54:15.060 --> 00:54:22.370
that what was your most favorite
thing when you was in the Army?

00:54:22.370 --> 00:54:23.980
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: You asked
what's the most favorite thing

00:54:23.980 --> 00:54:25.280
when I was in the Army.

00:54:25.280 --> 00:54:40.060
Well, it was usually Saturday
night but we weren't on duty then.

00:54:40.060 --> 00:54:48.200 position:56%
When I was on duty and doing my job,
I really liked and analyzed things.

00:54:48.200 --> 00:54:52.220
I liked to say -- I liked to look
at the terrain and ask the question

00:54:52.220 --> 00:54:58.520
if I were the enemy,
where would I be.

00:54:58.520 --> 00:55:00.810
And try to figure that out.

00:55:00.810 --> 00:55:07.880
And if you can do that, then
you can defend yourself better.

00:55:11.750 --> 00:55:16.920
I liked to make organizations work.

00:55:16.920 --> 00:55:21.800
And later on that became favorite.

00:55:21.800 --> 00:55:28.630
But in the beginning, it was
down in the weeds doing the math,

00:55:28.630 --> 00:55:31.990
doing the calculations, thinking

00:55:31.990 --> 00:55:34.660
about what the enemy
was trying to do to us.

00:55:34.660 --> 00:55:35.960
Yes sir.

00:55:35.960 --> 00:55:42.890
&gt;&gt; My name Isaiah and what was
the most important thing that --

00:55:42.890 --> 00:55:45.610
What was the most important
thing that you had

00:55:45.610 --> 00:55:49.540
to learn during the Army?

00:55:49.540 --> 00:55:52.120
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: Ask for help.

00:55:54.270 --> 00:56:00.110
The question was what was the
most important thing that I had

00:56:00.110 --> 00:56:04.670
to learn to do in the Army.

00:56:04.670 --> 00:56:10.970 position:56%
Well, you walk in as this brand new
second lieutenant and every sergeant

00:56:10.970 --> 00:56:17.660 position:56%
in the unit has been there and knows
more about their job than you do.

00:56:17.660 --> 00:56:22.330
Your job isn't to tell
them how to do their job.

00:56:22.330 --> 00:56:26.620
As a lieutenant, you have to
learn can they do their job,

00:56:26.620 --> 00:56:30.140
do they do it well,
can they do their job

00:56:30.140 --> 00:56:35.040
without messing somebody else up
because it doesn't do any good

00:56:35.040 --> 00:56:38.290 position:56%
to do your job if you've made
somebody else's life more difficult.

00:56:38.290 --> 00:56:41.930
You had to learn to
ask them for help.

00:56:41.930 --> 00:56:47.750
You had to learn to ask
the question, serg, chief,

00:56:47.750 --> 00:56:53.190
is this is a sergeant problem
or is this an officer problem.

00:56:53.190 --> 00:56:56.540 position:56%
Inevitably, the sergeant said,
well, let me take a look at it first

00:56:56.540 --> 00:56:59.140
and if I can't handle it,
it's an officer problem.

00:56:59.140 --> 00:57:08.550
And, you know, only one or two
times did I ever get a problem.

00:57:08.550 --> 00:57:14.100
But learning that and learning
how to make that work for you,

00:57:14.100 --> 00:57:15.460
that was all after school.

00:57:15.460 --> 00:57:17.180
That was on-the-job training.

00:57:17.180 --> 00:57:19.810
Yes sir. Thank you.

00:57:19.810 --> 00:57:21.370
&gt;&gt; I know you guys have leave.

00:57:21.370 --> 00:57:29.480
And when you are on leave, what
did you do for fun or [inaudible]?

00:57:29.480 --> 00:57:33.330
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: The unit
I was in, in Vietnam chose

00:57:33.330 --> 00:57:39.770
to let their officers have leave,
R&amp;R, after 11 months in country.

00:57:44.410 --> 00:57:48.510 position:56%
I never got to 11 months in country.

00:57:48.510 --> 00:57:52.030
So I don't know.

00:57:52.030 --> 00:57:54.840
Your choice was go to Bangkok,

00:57:54.840 --> 00:57:58.530
see an incredible culture
that's very different from ours.

00:57:58.530 --> 00:58:02.760
Go to Australia, see an English
speaking culture that's very

00:58:02.760 --> 00:58:04.220
different from ours.

00:58:04.220 --> 00:58:08.980 position:56%
Go to Hong Kong, get a suit made
that's going to be too small for you

00:58:08.980 --> 00:58:11.500
because when you get home
you're going to put on weight.

00:58:11.500 --> 00:58:18.900
I don't know where
I was going to go.

00:58:18.900 --> 00:58:28.380
With an older audience, I would say
what that did was in that battalion

00:58:28.380 --> 00:58:33.200
after you went on R&amp;R,
you were given light duty

00:58:33.200 --> 00:58:35.900
and you were never
sent back to the field.

00:58:35.900 --> 00:58:39.400
And then you went home.

00:58:39.400 --> 00:58:43.400
So that was the mindset
about the command decision

00:58:43.400 --> 00:58:48.380
about not giving R&amp;R
midway in between.

00:58:48.380 --> 00:58:51.620
It was a command decision
and it was for the good

00:58:51.620 --> 00:58:58.550
of the battalion, not
immediately obvious.

00:58:58.550 --> 00:59:05.820
I think people are getting
antsy, just a little.

00:59:05.820 --> 00:59:08.440
Are there some more questions?

00:59:08.440 --> 00:59:10.510
Yes ma'am.

00:59:10.510 --> 00:59:17.400
&gt;&gt; Okay, I asked the same question.

00:59:17.400 --> 00:59:22.260
What was the funniest thing
that you have [inaudible]?

00:59:22.260 --> 00:59:26.290
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: Funniest thing?

00:59:26.290 --> 00:59:35.080
The funniest thing that happened
to me in the Army was when you pull

00:59:35.080 --> 00:59:43.810
in to a firing site and the
XO, the officer in charge,

00:59:43.810 --> 00:59:51.480
has to point the direction that he
wants the artillery tubes to point.

00:59:51.480 --> 00:59:56.260
The first time that I pulled the
firing battery into a firing point

00:59:56.260 --> 01:00:02.360
and wanted them to align on the
direction, I went like this.

01:00:02.360 --> 01:00:08.130
And the chief sergeant said, sir,
which way do you want the tubes

01:00:08.130 --> 01:00:11.710
to point, this way or this way?

01:00:17.290 --> 01:00:24.550
He needed to know from me which
way and I didn't give it to him.

01:00:24.550 --> 01:00:27.680
I just gave him an
azimuth direction.

01:00:27.680 --> 01:00:32.370
I didn't point him in
the right direction.

01:00:32.370 --> 01:00:38.780
It was a learning experience for
me but I was also the subject

01:00:38.780 --> 01:00:45.950 position:56%
of laughter that evening in the BOQ,
where all the officers were sleeping

01:00:45.950 --> 01:00:49.410
in the same room, dorm style.

01:00:49.410 --> 01:00:55.880
Everybody in the battalion learned
that you point this way, this way,

01:00:55.880 --> 01:01:00.710
this way, but don't do it this way.

01:01:00.710 --> 01:01:04.560
And I was the butt of
the joke for a night.

01:01:04.560 --> 01:01:05.940
Yes sir?

01:01:05.940 --> 01:01:08.020
[ Inaudible Question ]

01:01:08.020 --> 01:01:10.520
&gt;&gt; My name is Mawqua [phonetic]

01:01:10.520 --> 01:01:14.660
and what is your favorite weapon
while you were in the war?

01:01:16.270 --> 01:01:19.130
&gt;&gt; Brian Thacker: What
was my favorite weapon?

01:01:19.130 --> 01:01:24.240
My favorite weapon was
one that I didn't have.

01:01:24.240 --> 01:01:29.800
An artillery piece in those
days was an eight-inch howitzer.

01:01:29.800 --> 01:01:32.950
It's big. It's mean.

01:01:32.950 --> 01:01:37.820
When it hits somebody, it
really kicks your butt.

01:01:37.820 --> 01:01:42.020
But it's very accurate
for a weapon that big.

01:01:42.020 --> 01:01:52.930
And that was the weapon I needed
most the day of the action.

01:01:52.930 --> 01:01:57.200
I would've loved to have been
on the wrong end of that weapon

01:01:57.200 --> 01:01:59.660
because it would've missed me by --

01:01:59.660 --> 01:02:01.850
If I had asked it to
miss me by 50 meters,

01:02:01.850 --> 01:02:03.490
it would've missed me by 50 meters.

01:02:03.490 --> 01:02:06.480
If I had asked it to
miss me by 10 meters,

01:02:06.480 --> 01:02:09.340
it would've missed me by 10 meters.

01:02:09.340 --> 01:02:11.990
That weapon is that good.

01:02:13.090 --> 01:02:15.960
And that's what I needed
and I didn't have it.

01:02:19.530 --> 01:02:22.960
It's not the answer you
were expecting, I'll bet.

01:02:22.960 --> 01:02:26.130
&gt;&gt; Karen Jaffe: Okay,
well thank you so much.

01:02:26.130 --> 01:02:29.850
You want to give Brian a
round of applause [applause].

